					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Iksar Beastlord Newbie guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Slick</a> | 
		            2/4/2003 12:52:08 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Welcome to my Iksar Beastlord Newbie guide. I noticed that there were no Iksar Beastlord guides on Everlore so I thought I'd offer my own<BR>
experiences of being this most unusual of race and class. This is guide is by no means exhaustive as I have only got to level  11, but I can give you an insight into the nature of being a lowbie Beastlord and where to hunt in<BR>
the lands of Kunark.<BR>
<BR>
Please note the character I created and used as a basis for this guide is completely un-twinked, so this guide is for all you true  noobs out there:-) For your info, I put the majority of my points into wisdom when I created my character, and the rest into  agility. Do what you like here<BR>
really, if you want to use spells then invest in WIS, if you want to hit hard then invest in STR. At the  end of the day, it really doesn't matter<BR>
too much as long as you like your character.<BR>
<BR>
So why go an Iksar Beastlord? As usual, the primary considerations are taking into account the advantages and disadvantages of taking this race and class. <BR>
<BR>
Obvious disadvantages for an Iksar Beastlord are:<BR>
<BR>
1) Racial hatred. You are pretty much despised everywhere except Kunark. A lot of NPC's regard you as Kill On Sight (KOS) so you  must be on your guard to con NPC's regularly, especially near towns. This makes travel difficult unless you have a high level Druid or   Wizard pal, or you own the Planes of Power expansion (this lets you transport to most major places and puts you<BR>
in a nice safe  place out of the way or guards etc). For this reason alone I recommend you purchase Planes of Power as it makes the life of an  Iksar Beastlord (or any Iksar to be honest) more bearable. Don't get me wrong, you can theoretically hunt up to very high levels on  Kunark - it's just more fun to travel elsewhere and meet new people. You can also get to the Nexus to by uber items with ease -  when you get some hard cash of course.<BR>
<BR>
2) As a Beastlord you don't get your pet until lv9. This means you have to brave the wilderness by yourself until your loyal pocket  Godzilla realises its calling and joins your side. As a Beastlord, you inherit some Monk-like abilities so you could do worse than make  use of  these. I specialised in Hand to Hand for the first time, but at the end of the day you can use any<BR>
skill that you want. If you  can afford a high damage weapon then by all means specialise in this. Some people say you should max out all your combat skills,  but this just bores me to be honest. I'd rather hit most of the time than keep changing weapons and try and level up skills. Once  you know what weapons you like or want in the game, then tailor your combat skills<BR>
for them.<BR>
<BR>
3) Experience disadvantage. As an Iksar, you won't level up as fast as some other races but who cares? You get a mini dinosaur and  that makes up for it, trust me. <BR>
<BR>
Obvious Advantages for an Iksar Beastlord are:<BR>
<BR>
1) Regeneration. This is an obvious boon, as<BR>
while you are sitting down you will regenerate 4 points of HP every 6 seconds. I should imagine that this becomes harder to appreciate at higher levels, but when you are up to level 9 it just seems to fly by. Compared to most races, you<BR>
will be back in the fight well before they are. Just be careful of wandering monsters whilst you<BR>
are sitting  down. Monsters that don't attack you while standing will sometimes bundle you when you are sitting down if they don't like you.<BR>
<BR>
2) Good natural AC. Your armour class is pretty good for an essentially unarmoured character. Of course, you can buy certain  armour  to increase<BR>
this further and be even better. Up to level 9 though, I noticed I could sustain quite a lot of hits from yellow  cons and still come out on top. I did have some newbie quest armour (more on this later) and a 2pp cloak purchased from a  shopkeeper but that was it.<BR>
<BR>
3) Your pet. When you reach level 9 your pet becomes your best buddy. Use it often to help damage Mobs (even solo some!), but  also use it as a life saver. If in doubt, let the pet die if it will save your life (and experience). Pets can also be a right royal pain in  the arse if they aggro too many Mobs. Many a time I have sat there trying to tell my pet to return<BR>
and the thing stubbornly  refuses. Suddenly the pet dies and have half of Kunark chasing you across the open plains :-) Get used to when you should use a  pet and when you shouldn't and you'll be fine. Also remember that if<BR>
a pet does more than 50% damage to a mob then it will nick  half the experience for the kill. With that it mind, you are usually always better<BR>
off tanking in addition to your pet.<BR>
<BR>
4) Spells. You get some useful spells at level 9. Buy them all from the big castle in Cabilis (your starting area with your guild trainers)  and you will appreciate them a lot. You get a heal, several buffs, your pet spell and a pet heal too. You can also get a blindness spell but this is a bit crap so its up to you if you really want to use this. The aggro is produces<BR>
(along with the erratic running away) makes this a no-no for me. At level 9 your mana runs out pretty quick (at least until you get Meditate at level 12) but you  should keep casting spells to build up your skills. One day, you'll stop fizzling when casting. I promise.<BR>
<BR>
5) Swimming and Forage skills. You get these as default so you are a great swimmer and can forage your own nosh and water. The forage skill is exceptionally useful as you will often find it hard to buy food from non-Kunark zones. Swimming is pretty useful too, especially around Cabilis.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
So there you go. A very basic summary of the major strengths and weaknesses of an Iksar Beastlord. Even with my duff maths, I  personally count more advantages than disadvantages which might help convince some of you that being an Iksar isn't so bad. Other  races may have no major disadvantages, but everyone always picks those races. Try an Iksar Beastlord and defy convention!! Always  remember this..when was the last time you saw an Iksar<BR>
Beastlord on EQ? Me, I've never seen one before which is why I started one!<BR>
<BR>
HUNTING GUIDE:<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1-5:<BR>
<BR>
You will start as a humble level 1 and have 20 food and 20 milk as your primary nourishment. This will last you a while so don't worry  too much about food and water. By the time your original food and water have run out you should have plenty of foraged food  anyway. You will also have a note in your inventory which you should hand in to the Main Patriarch in front of<BR>
you (I forget his  name). Remember this guy as you will be coming back to him for some quests later. Hand your note to him and you will get an<BR>
amazing (!?) AC 2 tunic. Now get out to the Field of Bone and kick ass. If<BR>
you can't be bothered (or don't know how) to find your  way there from inside Cabilis then simply hit a friendy NPC and you will killed instantly. You will now respawn in the Field of Bone!<BR>
<BR>
Head out to the newbie zone (follow the path) and con any creatures you meet. At level 1 you should kill things that con white, like beetles and skeletons. To keep in character, I didn't kill the wolf pups as they are amiable to me. Be wary of beetles and  skeletons as they are social which means if you pull one then any close friends will come in and join the fight. Try and pull the  beetle or skelly to a safe area and press F9 to get an outside view. From here you can see all around and be more aware of your surroundings. Keep pressing F9 to get your view back. <BR>
<BR>
At level 2-4 you can hunt more skeletons, beetles, some spiders and scorpions. Only skellies and beetles are social out of these  still. You should start to level up in no time. Quick tip - collect Scorpion pincers and hand them into the warlord who is on the  balcony near the entrance to the Field of Bone. He will give you a small amount of money but you will get<BR>
a nice experience boost.  You can continue to do this up to level 5 before the experience is negligable.<BR>
<BR>
At level 5 go back to Cabilis and meet your Guild trainer. Learn the Kick skill and now you will become a little more powerful as you  essentially have a free attack every 6 seconds or so! At this point also 'hail' your<BR>
Guild trainer. Reply to his questions to begin your  first newbie quest. You can start these earlier if you want, but I think level 5 is a good time to start this. Your first quest involves  collecting 4 Leech Husks. You can<BR>
either cheat and buy these from the traders (if you have enough money) or you can go to the  Swamp of No Hope and kill Marsh Leeches for these. These should be light blue or even green to you so once you have 4 husks, go  back<BR>
to your Guild trainer and give him the husks. <BR>
<BR>
You will now be awarded with a No-Drop, Lore Bracer. You can now do quest two by answering his questions again. This time you  need a Scarab Carapace (from beetles in Field of Bone) and 3 Spiderling silks (from Spiders in<BR>
Field of Bone). Once you have these,  go back and give these to your Guild trainer to get another item (hat or trousers - I can't remember now). Answer some more  questions and he tells he wants 4 goblin watcher torches. These can be found on Goblin Watchers in the Lake of Ill Omen. This  zone can be accessed from Cabilis too. This is also an ideal place to hunt next...<BR>
<BR>
LEVEL 6 - 7:<BR>
<BR>
At this level you want to hunt at the Lake of Ill Omen. Stay close to the buildings as less things roam close here. The further you  move out, the more likely you are to get bundled. At this level, pick on anything that cons blue or white. This usually consits of  Skeletons, Goblin Scouts, Goblin Watchers and Sarnak Hatchlings. With regards to the Goblin Watchers,<BR>
collect four of their  torches and take these back to your Guild Trainer for another newbie armour item. The next quest item for you requires the collection of items from currently dark blue and white cons (at level 9). You need Goblin Hunter Spears (easy kills with your  pet) and 2 Sarnak Broodline fangs (very rare drop but easy kills). I get ahead of myself as you should be doing this at level 9 - so  when you reach level 8...<BR>
<BR>
LEVEL 8 - 9:<BR>
<BR>
Leave Lake of Ill Omen if you want and go back to the Field of Bone. Go through the Newbie area and head for the arena just  outside of the noob<BR>
zone. In here are some tasty kills to rack up experience points. It consists of mainly Scalebone Skellies, Iksar  Bandits, Scorpions, Scale Wolves and spiders. Remember to con everything, and remember that mostly all of these<BR>
are social now,  and will also attack you if you are in aggro range. Pull to the side if you can, as this will make things much easier. If you can find a team mate then things get even easier as you can kill yellow cons with ease and get great exp. I jumped from level 7 to 9 in around  2.5 hours. Before you know it you will be level 9 and you can go and get your lv9 spells. All<BR>
your spells can be purchased in your  starting Guild area from downstairs and upstairs (through the flashing red teleporters in the wall). Mem your spells, cast your Spirit  spell and, yay, you have a nice shiny pet.<BR>
<BR>
From here on in the world is your oyster. You can continue to kill Goblin Hunters in Lake of Ill Omen as these con white or yellow,  or you can venture out into the wide world and hunt in some other good places for your level. If you can avoid guards and NPC's I recommend going to North Ro (near East Commons) or Clan Crushbone (next to the Wood Elf city of Kelethin).  If you are very  careful, they are great areas for experience when in groups. You can get bound in Freeport for North Ro, or near the trees for  Kelethin so you don't have to always start back<BR>
on Kunark when (if!) you die. If you have the Planes of Power expansion then getting to these areas is dead easy. Without it, then you are better off hunting in Kunark - as I said before, you can pretty much  level up as high as you want on Kunark if you know where to hunt. I'm sure there are plenty of other places to hunt as well, and by  all means add these if you reply to<BR>
this post because this was never intended to be a definitive guide with just my comments. If you  ever need money (when don't you?) then I thoroughly recommend a trip to the Aqua Goblin camps in Butcherblock. You will be  KOS to all the guards, but you can sneak past them quite easily. If I can solo a camp then I can usually make well over 100pp in an  hour and a half. You<BR>
really want to do this at lv8 or 9 so you get exp as well as money, but that is entirely up to you. Your first  purchase after your new found wealth should be a Polished Steel Ulak (around 10pp) if you like Hand to Hand, and maybe a full set  of Wu's armour for starters (as it is quite cheap in the Nexus). Once you are kitted out nicely, you should be able to do some nice Hand to Hand damage (I hit for 19 at lv11).<BR>
<BR>
Well, I think I have jabbered on enough now and I think you should go on EQ and prove to the world that Iksar Beastlords rock. You  will all probably out-level me but I hope this guide helps one or two of you budding Iksar Beastlords, and if this is the case then my  job is done and I'll be a happy lizard. <BR>
<BR>
By all means send me a tell on the new Venril Sethir (UK) server! Happy hunting!<BR>
<BR>
Kroxigor<BR>
<BR>
Beastlord of the 11th Season
